description:
Large-scale reasoning models (LRMs) rely on long-chain reasoning to improve performance on complex tasks, but they inherently suffer from a structural problem: an imbalance between redundant reasoning steps and semantic contributions, meaning "not all generation steps contribute the necessary amount to the final answer." Existing methods often address this issue through pruning or external constraints, lacking modeling of the intrinsic optimal matching relationship between "reasoning steps and semantic contributions."  
 &nbsp; 
  This paper proposes a novel training paradigm: Optimal Reasoning Assignment Tuning (ORAT). This method introduces the **Assignment Problem** into the optimization of reasoning trajectories in large models for the first time, formalizing the reasoning process as an optimal binary matching problem between the "set of steps" and the "set of semantic contributions from latent variables." By constructing a "Reasoning Contribution Matrix," we transform the reasoning compression problem into a dynamic optimal assignment problem and learn the "optimal reasoning path matching strategy" during training.  
 &nbsp; 
  This method not only automatically eliminates redundant reasoning steps but also optimizes the reasoning structure while maintaining reasoning correctness, enabling the model to learn "structurally optimal thought paths" rather than "length-dependent thought paths."

